TEXT.22: Data are derived from a time-of-flight mass spectrograph

TEXT.24: individual ion species over the energy range 1 - 12000 eV,

TEXT.26: instrument consists of a toroidal top-hat electrostatic

TEXT.27: analyzer with instantaneous acceptance of ions over 360

TEXT.28: degrees in polar angle in 16 sectors.  Ions passing

TEXT.29: through the electrostatic analyzer are postaccelerated by

TEXT.30: up to 25 kV and then analyzed for mass per charge in a

TEXT.31: foil-based time-of-flight analyzer.  The data used to

TEXT.32: construct CDF data products are derived from the Survey

TEXT.34: 4 mass groups x 48 energies x 64 solid angle segments.

TEXT.35: The 4 mass groups are H+, O+, He+, and He++.  Only the

TEXT.36: 16 equatorial angle segments are used for the CDF data set.

TEXT.37: Each equatorial solid angle segment contains 2 (4) samples

TEXT.38: at each energy in the 32 (64) sweep/spin mode.  The full

TEXT.39: angular range is covered in half a spin but the actual

TEXT.40: time resolution of the survey data product depends upon

TEXT.41: the telemetry mode.  In the highest TM rate modes H+ and O+

TEXT.42: survey data read out every half spin.  In lowest TM rate

TEXT.43: mode these data are accumulated for 4 spins.  The minimum

TEXT.44: accumulation time included in the CDF is 1 spin, so if the

TEXT.45: actual accumulation time is a half spin, two data points

TEXT.46: are averaged.  Otherwise, the full resolution is included.

TEXT.47: In every mode He+ and He++ are accumulated twice as long

TEXT.48: as H+ and O+.  To force the H+, O+, and He+ to have an

TEXT.49: equal number of data points when H+ and O+ have twice the

TEXT.50: time resolution, each He+ data point is written twice
